{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011W9KyCCMRpm1VXmf4489xX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully.\n\n**Behavior 1**: Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves getting the list of changed files from GitHub API or git diff, then filtering which files to analyze. The failure mode is about correctly identifying changed files from the PR context. This could be a unit test if the filtering logic is isolated, but the actual list of changed files comes from GitHub API or git context. \n- REAL-INFRA: The files come from GitHub PR context (real HTTP/API) or git commands (subprocess).\n- MOCK-HIDE: If we mock the GitHub API response, we can test the filtering logic in isolation. \n\nThe core question is whether the behavior can be tested without real GitHub API calls. The filtering logic itself is unit-testable if I provide a mock list of changed files, but the actual determination of which files changed requires either real GitHub API interaction or git subprocess calls. This feels like an integration test at minimum since the failure could surface at the boundary between the file-fetching module and the analysis module.\n\nFor the grouping behavior, I'm looking at whether findings can be organized by severity and formatted into a comment. This is purely formatting logic.\n\nFor the performance requirement with 200 files, I need to actually run the analysis and measure execution time against the 10-minute timeout. This requires real subprocess execution and file I/O, so it needs System-level testing.\n\nFor the crash handling behavior, I could test this at the Integration level by mocking the subprocess to return a failure code or exception, then verifying the pipeline continues processing remaining files rather than halting.\n\nFor deduplication, this is straightforward Unit-level logic—I'm testing a pure function that takes a list of findings and removes duplicates, so I don't need any infrastructure mocking.\n\nLet me finalize the test levels for each behavior. The key failure mode: the system might scan ALL files instead of just changed ones. Testing this requires wiring the \"get changed files\" module with the \"scan files\" module. You need to verify that the list of changed files (from whatever source - can be mocked) correctly filters what gets scanned. Integration seems right.\n\n**Behavior 2** - Unit\nPure formatting/grouping logic. Unit.\n\n**Behavior 3** - System\nPerformance test, needs real execution with real subprocesses and file I/O.\n\n**Behavior 4** - Integration\nError handling when linter crashes. Can mock the subprocess to simulate crash, test that iteration continues.\n\n**Behavior 5** - Unit\nPure deduplication algorithm. Unit.\n\nNow I'm checking whether each behavior is at the right test level. Behavior 1 could be System if changed-file detection required real GitHub API calls, but mocking those responses keeps it at Integration. Behavior 2's grouping logic is self-contained enough for Unit testing. Behavior 3 definitely needs System-level testing since mocking subprocess calls would hide performance failures. For Behavior 4, the real concern is whether remaining files get analyzed after a crash—this requires the file iteration loop and error handler working together, so Integration testing with mocked subprocess failures is the right approach.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9530,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9530},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a51ea4c1-6913-41c6-ad11-306727947f78","uuid":"97bf2ce3-4a7d-4f62-bf03-d456cbee9c52"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011W9KyCCMRpm1VXmf4489xX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01QFq7cBVAtTcevNuU54gufn","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed — unchanged files are not scanned.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is at the boundary between the changed-file resolver (GitHub API / git diff) and the file-analysis dispatcher. A Unit test of filtering logic alone can't catch a bug where the wrong file list is fetched and passed through. You need both modules wired together. REAL-INFRA: The GitHub API can be stubbed (no real network needed), so System is not required. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the file resolver in isolation would always pass; you need to verify the resolver's output is actually what drives which files the scanner opens. REJECTION-GATE for System: the changed-file list can be injected via a test double of the GitHub API client, so no real HTTP call is necessary to catch this class of bug.","test_description":"Set up a local repo with several files, mock the GitHub API client to return a specific changed-file list (e.g., only file_a.py), wire it to the real analysis dispatcher, run the pipeline, and assert that only file_a.py was passed to the linter — not any other file present in the working tree.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Findings are grouped by severity (error, warning, info) in the posted PR comment.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Grouping-by-severity is a self-contained transformation: input is a list of finding objects, output is a formatted string or data structure. No module boundary is crossed; the bug would live entirely inside a single function or class. REAL-INFRA: No filesystem, network, or subprocess is needed. MOCK-HIDE: There is nothing to mock — the logic is pure. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: escalating would only be needed if the findings list is assembled by a pipeline that garbles severity values before reaching this function; but the behavior targets the grouping step itself, not the upstream assembly.","test_description":"Construct a list of finding objects with mixed severities (e.g., two errors, one warning, one info) using real model/data classes. Call the grouping function directly. Assert the returned structure has exactly the right findings under each severity key and that the formatted comment contains the correct section headers.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A pull request that touches 200 files completes analysis within the 10-minute Actions timeout.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Performance is not a logical property; it is an emergent property of real I/O, process spawning latency, and scheduling. REAL-INFRA: The linter runs as a subprocess per file (or in batches). Real subprocess spawn cost, file-read time, and CPU scheduling are all load-bearing for this constraint. Mocking subprocess calls would make 200 iterations instantaneous, trivially passing the timing assertion and hiding any real bottleneck. MOCK-HIDE: Yes — any mock collapses wall-clock time to near zero, so mocking always passes, making the test meaningless. REJECTION-GATE for Agentic: correctness here is deterministic wall-clock time, not probabilistic ML output; no LLM or AI model is involved in the timing measurement itself.","test_description":"Generate 200 small but syntactically varied real source files on the local filesystem. Run the full pipeline binary (or entry-point script) as a subprocess against those files, recording wall-clock elapsed time. Assert total elapsed time is under 600 seconds. Flag slow per-file averages as secondary diagnostics.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.82,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the linter process crashes on a malformed file, the remaining files are still analyzed and results posted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode appears at the boundary between the per-file subprocess invocation and the iteration/aggregation loop. A Unit test of the loop logic alone (with a fake callable) could work, but the real risk is whether the caller correctly catches the subprocess exception type (CalledProcessError, OSError, etc.) and continues. Wiring the real exception-catching code with the real dispatch loop is needed. REAL-INFRA: A real crashing subprocess is not required; patch.object on the subprocess runner to raise CalledProcessError is sufficient and catches the real failure class. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking at the right granularity (the subprocess interface, not the entire linter module) does not hide the failure. REJECTION-GATE for System: no real process crash is needed because the exception path through the code is exercised by injecting the exception via the mock.","test_description":"Prepare three file paths; mock the subprocess runner so it raises CalledProcessError on the second file and returns success stubs for the first and third. Wire the mock into the real analysis orchestrator. Run the orchestrator. Assert that findings from files 1 and 3 are present in the final output and the error for file 2 is recorded but does not abort processing.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate findings on the same line from overlapping rules are deduplicated in the output.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Deduplication is a pure algorithmic transformation over a collection of finding objects. The bug either lives in the dedup function's equality/hashing logic or it doesn't; no other module needs to be present. REAL-INFRA: No I/O or subprocess is involved. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing to mock. REJECTION-GATE for Integration: escalation would be warranted only if overlapping rules produce findings in a format that the dedup step never receives correctly — but the behavior statement targets the dedup output, not upstream rule execution, so the input list can be constructed directly in the test.","test_description":"Construct a list of finding objects that includes exact duplicates (same file, line, rule, message) and near-duplicates (same line but different rule). Call the deduplication function directly. Assert the returned list contains each unique (file, line, rule, message) tuple exactly once, and that near-duplicates on the same line but from different rules are preserved as distinct entries.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.16,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9530,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9530},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a51ea4c1-6913-41c6-ad11-306727947f78","uuid":"85c4c61a-7583-4682-812f-426b8d16ab46"}
